We send our prayers and condolences to the Frazier and Caldwell family in Dallas and Oklahoma. Ruth and Mike Frazier have always been integrated into the community of sports, education, and church. Ruth Frazier leaves a legacy that is felt in the community. Her loving family with open arms welcomed new people and those coming out of town. Ruth’s family has always carried her DNA etiquette of making sure everyone was cared for. If they were cooking it was always made for more. Her circles were large from the numbers of her families to her Aunts and Uncles and their family extensions. It almost became a big gathering over food, especially during the Choctaw festival at Tushkahoma. People just walking around early in the morning in the morning dew or when the sunset was setting, the Frazier compound was just another home, to meet others, or to wait for the next softball game. That was Ruth Frazier’s ripple of affection and comfort. It was always family, and her family lived through her examples of loving life. Ruth Frazier was a part of the 2021 AIHD Book project that focused on the beginnings of the Indian Relocation Act and how American Indians gathered to create a community of inter-tribal citizens to call Dallas home. Of course, it was how the softball ecosystem became a staple in Dallas, how teams formed, from individuals bringing the game they loved to the community to have a social atmosphere, to build a stronger glue of people coming into the community. Ruth Frazier contributed to the book. Good memories of how life was in the past and how time was captured in moments of love and it brings tearful memories of Ruth Frazier. You see your time incapsulated in the memories tied to an individual and those memories of good and bad or comforting come like a flood at the right moment. You see a person that has been at most every timeline since the birth for those today and she was one of those beloved elders, she was community. We were asked to share from the heart but her heart was the best example of our Dallas a community that needs to be shared, followed, and preserved as American Indians to open their heart to others. Please remember the Frazier Family as they prepare the RUTH FRAZIER celebration of life. Ruth Frazier Niki Branch Juan Dlr Michael Frazier Michael Frazier leadership from generation to generation. We acknowledge that we are gathered on stolen land. We are on the traditional land of our ancestors who sacrificed their lives for our existence. Biography of CASEY DOUMA Casey Douma (Laguna Pueblo/Hopi-Tewa) is an attorney and owner of Douma Law, P.C., and works on behalf of tribal nations, tribal entities, and other organizations that impact the lives of Indigenous people. He attended Haskell Indian Nations University and earned a Bachelors's Degree in Business Administration. Casey received his Juris Doctorate Degree from the University of New Mexico School of Law with an Indian Law Certificate. He received an LL.M. Degree in Indigenous Peoples Law and Policy from the University of Arizona College of Law. Casey started his legal career giving back to his tribe as a Prosecutor and then as an In-House Legal Counsel for Laguna Pueblo while serving as an adjunct professor at the University of New Mexico Law School, teaching Indian Law courses. Casey is also Senior Faculty with the Leadership Institute, teaching and mentoring youth in the Summer Policy Academy at Princeton University, Washington, D.C., and the United Nations. Currently, Casey sits as a Board Chair for the New Mexico Center on Law and Poverty and is an Associate Justice with the Chippewa Cree Tribe Court of Appeals. Mr. Douma wears many hats, working on tribal court development, repatriation, indigenous customary laws, nation-building, education, and federal Indian law. Casey is strongly connected to his tribal communities of Laguna Pueblo in New Mexico and Hopi-Tewa in Arizona while living in the White Mountains of Arizona with his wife and three 2pm / Central Time Zone Join us by going onto our AIHD page to view the FB Live presentation. . . . . . . . . . . . “2021 American Indian Heritage Day in Texas Themed: Sovereignty” Sovereignty is celebrating the historical matrilineal leadership from generation to generation. We acknowledge that we are gathered on stolen land. We are on the traditional land of our ancestors who sacrificed their lives for our existence.    Biography of CASEY DOUMA Casey Douma (Laguna Pueblo/Hopi-Tewa) is an attorney and owner of Douma Law, P.C., and works on behalf of tribal nations, tribal entities, and other organizations that impact the lives of Indigenous people. He attended Haskell Indian Nations University and earned a Bachelors's Degree in Business Administration. Casey received his Juris Doctorate Degree from the University of New Mexico School of Law with an Indian Law Certificate. He received an LL.M. Degree in Indigenous Peoples Law and Policy from the University of Arizona College of Law. Casey started his legal career giving back to his tribe as a Prosecutor and then as an In-House Legal Counsel for Laguna Pueblo while serving as an adjunct professor at the University of New Mexico Law School, teaching Indian Law courses. Casey is also Senior Faculty with the Leadership Institute, teaching and mentoring youth in the Summer Policy Academy at Princeton University, Washington, D.C., and the United Nations. Currently, Casey sits as a Board Chair for the New Mexico Center on Law and Poverty and is an Associate Justice with the Chippewa Cree Tribe Court of Appeals. Mr. Douma wears many hats, working on tribal court development, repatriation, indigenous customary laws, nation-building, education, and federal Indian law. Casey is strongly connected to his tribal communities of Laguna Pueblo in New Mexico and Hopi-Tewa in Arizona while living in the White Mountains of Arizona with his wife and three children. vaccinated and undergo testing and contact tracing. Jeffrey Zients, coronavirus response coordinator for President Joe Biden, told reporters the new \"consistent approach\" would take effect \"early November.\" The easing of travel restrictions, imposed 18 months ago by Donald Trump as the Covid-19 pandemic first erupted, marks a significant shift by Biden and answers a major demand from European allies at a time of strained diplomatic relations. Numerous safeguards will remain in place to suppress the spread of the virus, which has already killed more than 670,000 Americans and is resurgent after what many had hoped was a lasting dip earlier this year. \"Most importantly, foreign nationals flying to the US will be required to be fully vaccinated,\" Zients said. It wasn't immediately clear if the new rule only applied to US-approved vaccines or if other brands, such as those produced in China or Russia would also qualify. Zients said that would be determined by the US Centers for Disease Control. Restrictions on vehicle movement from Canada and Mexico will remain in place. \"We do not have any updates on the land border policies,\" Zients said. Zients said passengers will need to show they were fully vaccinated before boarding planes to the United States, as well as providing proof of a negative Covid-19 test taken within three days. Americans not fully vaccinated will still be able to enter but only on testing negative within a day of travel. The announcement was quickly welcomed by the trade group Airlines For Europe, which said \"this decision will give a much-needed boost to trans-Atlantic traffic & tourism and will reunite families and friends.\" But while it had been widely expected that Biden would reopen borders to the European Union and Britain, the announcement covers the globe. \"This applies to all international travel,\" Zients said. Currently only US citizens, residents and foreigners with special visas are allowed to enter the United States from most European countries. The restriction has deeply irked EU and British authorities. On Monday, the European Union recommended that member states reimpose restrictions on American travelers who had earlier been free to enter if vaccinated. Biden's move comes on the eve of his speech to the annual UN General Assembly in New York, where the pandemic is due to be the headline issue. Many know the river as the Trinity River. This is a Sovereignty historical thread that needs to be healed from the Caddo people that built Dallas through the equity of Import/Export trade to create the City of Dallas . . . . . . . . . . . . . Sovereignty is celebrating the historical matrilineal leadership from generation to generation. We acknowledge that we are gathered on stolen land. We are on the traditional land of our ancestors who sacrificed their lives for our existence. The usual constitutional concept of racial equality, and the older concept of race as well as the evolving definitions, do not adequately encompass the political and legal status of American Indians. Uniquely, equality issues arise from the American Indian’s status as tribal sovereignty. We are building a new ecosystem in the effort to bring “truth” to the American Indians. Organized religions often made significant efforts to destroy or take away the truth that the American Indian people already had and to demolish their cultural heritage. A better way would have been to take the time to see the truth and beauty existing within the cultures, the power, and healing that blessed the people through the ceremonies and medicines. It can be argued convincingly that, were it not for the strengthening ceremonies, medicines, and understandings, the American Indians would have been wiped out culturally. We reverse centuries of inequities for American Indians in national civil rights, social injustice, and the struggles of American Indian communities. We need to amplify the stories, art, culture preservation, and historical accuracy as we reclaim our preservation and become advocates for our people and our land . . . . . . . . . . . . . We are still working within the guidelines from Lone Star Park that are working beyond the guidelines for the safety of our Elders, parents, and our future to prevent the spread of Covid-19. Edition Edition // Shirt Design September 25, 2021, Starts at 10 am Lone Star Park Grand Prairie, Texas #onChickasawLand Mother Earth has provided us with water to nourish, purify and grow from her gifts as we say thank you from our ceremonies. We are in the stages of reclaiming our namesake and making requests in the form of resolutions for the City of Dallas to honor our ancestors in equity to start the process to claim the original name of the river that runs by Downtown Dallas to “Arkikosa” which was named from the people of the Caddo Nation. Many know the river as the Trinity River. This is a Sovereignty historical thread that needs to be healed from the Caddo people that built Dallas through the equity of Import/Export trade to create the City of Dallas . . . . . . . . . . . . . Sovereignty is celebrating the historical matrilineal leadership from generation to generation. We acknowledge that we are gathered on stolen land. We are on the traditional land of our ancestors who sacrificed their lives for our existence. The usual constitutional concept of racial equality, and the older concept of race as well as the evolving definitions, do not adequately encompass the political and legal status of American Indians. Uniquely, equality issues arise from the American Indian’s status as tribal sovereignty. We are building a new ecosystem in the effort to bring “truth” to the American Indians. Organized religions often made significant efforts to destroy or take away the truth that the American Indian people already had and to demolish their cultural heritage. A better way would have been to take the time to see the truth and beauty existing within the cultures, the power, and healing that blessed the people through the ceremonies and medicines. It can be argued convincingly that, were it not for the strengthening ceremonies, medicines, and understandings, the American Indians would have been wiped out culturally. We reverse centuries of inequities for American Indians in national civil rights, social injustice, and the struggles of American Indian communities. We need to amplify the stories, art, culture preservation, and historical accuracy as we reclaim our preservation and become advocates for our people and our land . . . . . . . . . . . . . We are still working within the guidelines from Lone Star Park that are working beyond the guidelines for the safety of our Elders, parents, and our future to prevent the spread of Covid-19. Acharya ji very gracefully accommodated the restrictions we had from the venue due to COVID. I truly thank him for his creativity and flexibility to accommodate the venue. In addition, our daughter wanted to have wedding based upon “Shri Krishan Rukmani Swayambher”, a wedding based on Lord Shri Krishna. I contacted Acharya ji to discuss. To my surprise he said ”no problem, we can figure it out , give me few days”. I contacted my Guru ji in India and asked them how they do it in India. They sent me some information thru email. I passed it along to Acharya ji. He was very willing to take what I sent and did his own extensive research and made it happen. I truly appreciate all his positive attitude and welcoming nature that encouraged us to do a wedding that would have not been possible without the willingness and support of Acharya ji. His knowledge and command of Sanskrit were commendable. Not only did Acharya ji put together a wedding he had not done before but also translated everything in English so all in the wedding could understand. Lots of people came to us and to Acharya ji and told him how much they all enjoyed being part of a different type of wedding. Acharya ji’s kind and humble demeaner and his positivity is what makes him a true “Pandit / Acharya”. Cincinnati community is blessed to have a head priest as him. I truly thank Hindu temple for their support and everything Acharya ji did to make this wedding a success. Please pass this along to Acharya ji with all my regards. Marie Tribe of Chippewa Indians; the Little Traverse Bay Bands of Odawa Indians; the Grand Traverse Band of Ottawa and Chippewa Indians; the Little River Band of Ottawa Indians; the Match-E-Be-Nash-She-Wish Band of Potawatomi; the Pokagon Band of Potawatomi; the Nottawaseppi Huron Band of the Potawatomi, and the Saginaw Chippewa Indian Tribe. \n\nThe Anishinaabe, Ojibwe, Odawa, and Potawatomi people in these Tribal Nations carry and represent a history and presence that goes back centuries. Furthermore, from our oldest ancestors to our youngest child today, our indigenous relatives and Tribal Nations in the State of Michigan have contributed much to the State’s success, history, economy, politics, and cultural heritage. Even the name Michigan is derived from the anishinaabemowin word michigami meaning “great lake.” From the invention of canoes, the development of maple syrup, creation of snowshoes, utilization of cradleboards, stabilization of crops, cultivation of medicines, protection of treaty rights and traditional lifeways, or guarding of land, water, and sacred sites, there are many things to be proud of as an indigenous person in Michigan. \n\nPlease take a moment today to acknowledge all that we have accomplished past, present, and future; and also to remember the true history of the land that we reside on here in the State of Michigan. Route: Bangalore -> Male After 15 days stay. Male -> Doha (Qatar Airways)-> Chicago -> Residence in US (different state and city). Just sharing you all my experience... The first immigration officer in ORD looked into my passport and VISA and asked the following questions. So you are coming from India? I said No. I am coming from Maldives. Are you in H1B VISA? Yes When did you left US? I replied him with the date (around 5 months back). He took all 3 (myself, dad and mom) of us to another Immigration officer. We waited in that room for 15 minutes and he called. The second Immigration Officer asked the following questions. It took around 25 minutes. Here are questions.... Where are you coming from? Which is your home country? Why did you choose Maldives for 15 days stay? why not other countries? Initially I was planning to stay in Mex. Since the COVID cases are increasing in MEX, we choose Maldives which has very less number of cases compared to other countries. Also, it is very near to India. In case if we want to go back we will reach our country/state in 2 hours. How long did you stayed in Maldives? the date you reached Maldives and the date you started from Maldives. Where did you stayed in Maldives? xyz Resort from GAN Island. How did you spend your days in Maldives (15 days)? Why dont you apply for NIE and come directly to US rather than coming from a third country? Who is your employer? Is this the company you are working for ? or you are working for a different company through your employer? You were in India for the past 5 months. Are you still in Job? Yes. I have got the permission to work from Home and I am having my company laptop. I took leave for 2 or 3 days and worked rest of the days in US Timings. Did you get paid for the work you did while in India and Maldives? Yes. While in India for the past 5 months, did you go to any other state/city other than your hometown? Are you still with the same company? (mean... same company mentioned in VISA) What is your Home Address in India? and contact number in India. Where are you staying in US?.. and your US Contact number. After giving my US Apartment Address, next question is... So the past 5 months, who paid the rent for your apartment? Is there anyone staying in that apartment? So you paid the rent for the vacant apartment for the past 5 months? I answered Yes and similarly I have paid for Utilities, Internet and US Mobile Service too. Are you single/married? What is your Fathers occupation? and your mothers occupation? How long they are going to stay here in US? You are good to go. I answered all the questions honestly. He didn't asked me any proof/documents for verification other than I797. He documented all my answers and approved. Sharing this here for everyone who needs it. \"This inbox is for NIE Inquiries only for individuals with a valid and unexpired visa. If you do not have a valid visa, you cannot request a NIE and should schedule a visa appointment at www.ustraveldocs.com/in. Non-NIE related inquiries will not receive a response. Read the information below to see if your question has been addressed. How to Request a National Interest Exception (NIE)? Visa holders with definite plans to travel who can demonstrate qualification for a National Interest Exception may contact the Embassy or Consulate that issued their visa to request a national interest exception prior to travel: U.S.EmbassyNewDelhi: NewDelhiNIE@state.gov U.S. Consulate General Chennai: ChennaiNIE@state.gov U.S. Consulate General Hyderabad: HyderabadNIE@state.gov U.S. Consulate General Kolkata: KolkataNIE@state.gov U.S. Consulate General Mumbai: MumbaiNIE@state.gov The email must include the following information for all travelers seeking an exception, as it appears on the visa and attached valid, unexpired copies of the visas issued in Chennai for all travelers: Please note: Attachment file size should not exceed 300kb Surname (As per visa copy) : Given name (As per visa copy) : Date of birth (DD-MMM-YYYY) : Gender (M/F) : Country of birth : Country of citizenship: Passport number (Valid unexpired passport number only): Visa Class: Total no of Applicants: Issuing Post Name: Exact Travel date: Required Justification (see below) - For B1/B2 Humanitarian applicants please mention the life/death emergency that requires your immediate travel and any supporting documentation. -For all other visa holders please provide the requested information using the Primary Applicant's information in the format below. Job title: Company name: NIE Category (choose one from the list below): Urgent Medical (for B1/B2 humanitarian applicants only) Public Health Professional National Security Derivative Critical Infrastructure Journalist Pilot/Air Crew J1 Academic - If you selected Critical Infrastructure Category (choose one from the list below:) Information Technology Chemical Commercial Facilities Communications Critical Manufacturing Dams Defense Industrial Base Emergency Services Energy Financial Services Food and Agriculture Government Facilities Healthcare and Public Health Nuclear Reactors, Materials, and Waste Transportation Systems Water and Wastewater - You must include one sentence describing why the PRIMARY APPLICANT'S work duties requires their physical presence in the United States (i.e. they need to access hardware, customer data, inspect factories, treat patients, etc.) *The visa number, also known as the visa foil number, is located on the lower right of the visa. Each request will be carefully considered as our limited resources allow. Emails in languages other than English may slow response time. We aim to respond to each request within 30 days and in some cases longer. We cannot guarantee a decision date or the outcome of the decision. Errors in the submitted data may prevent approval in NIE requests. Themed: Sovereignty”\n\nSovereignty is celebrating the historical matrilineal leadership from generation to generation. We acknowledge that we are gathered on stolen land. We are on the traditional land of our ancestors who sacrificed their lives for our existence.   \n\nThe usual constitutional concept of racial equality, and the older concept of race as well as the evolving definitions, do not adequately encompass the political and legal status of American Indians. Uniquely, equality issues arise from the American Indian’s status as tribal sovereignty.  \n\nWe are building a new ecosystem in the effort to bring “truth” to the American Indians. Organized religions often made significant efforts to destroy or take away the truth that the American Indian people already had and to demolish their cultural heritage. A better way would have been to take the time to see the truth and beauty existing within the cultures, the power, and healing that blessed the people through the ceremonies and medicines. It can be argued convincingly that, were it not for the strengthening ceremonies, medicines, and understandings, the American Indians would have been wiped out culturally.  \n\nWe reverse centuries of inequities for American Indians in national civil rights, social injustice, and the struggles of American Indian communities. We need to amplify the stories, art, culture preservation, and historical accuracy as we reclaim our preservation and become advocates for our people and our land.\n\n  . . . . . . . . . . .  \n\nTribal Sovereignty is paramount.\n\nThe U.S. Constitution recognizes Indian tribes as distinct governments and they have, with a few exceptions, the same powers as federal and state governments to regulate their internal affairs.\n\nTribal Sovereignty includes the right to establish its form of government, determine membership requirements, enact legislation, and establish law enforcement, and court systems.   . . . . . . . . . . .\n\n• Tribal Sovereignty refers to the right of American Indians and Alaska Natives to govern themselves.  \n\n• Racial session or equality for change in training and learning insight shows the root of racism on this land from Doctrine of Discovery and Manifest Destiny.  \n\n• Indian Country honors the seeds of this land, giving gratitude to Mother Earth for protecting its people with nutrients and natural resources for the past, present, and future generations.\n \n• Mother Earth has been essential to the legacy. 12:55:32","updated":"2021-09-29 10:27:50","type":"photo","description":"What’s the meaning of Brahma Vishnu and Maheshwar in Hinduism\n\nBrahma-Vishnu-Shiva is the Hindu trinity, also called the trimurti. The Supreme Spirit or Universal Truth, called Brahman, is represented in three forms, each corresponding to one cosmic function, Brahma is the creator, Vishnu is the preserver and Shiva is the transformer or destroyer. Because Hinduism is a collection of different traditions and beliefs, scholars believe Brahma-Vishnu-Shiva was an attempt to reconcile the doctrine of Brahman with different approaches to the Divine. Of the three incarnations of Brahman, Shiva has a special place in the yogic traditions as he is considered the first yogi, or adiyogi. Shiva also symbolizes the balancing of awareness and bliss, and the calming effects of yoga practices in general.\n\nUnity with Brahman – which is personified as the trimurti  is the ultimate goal in yogic philosophy and practice. Today, Brahma-Vishnu-Shiva as the trimurti is rarely worshiped. Instead, Hindus typically worship one of the three as the supreme deity, and consider the others as incarnations of their supreme god. For example, Vaishnavism holds that Vishnu is the supreme god, while Shaivism believes that Shiva is supreme. Brahma, in comparison, has relatively few devotees as the supreme deity.\n\nIn ancient texts, the three gods symbolize earth, water and fire:\n\nBrahma represents earth. He is the originating power and creator of all life. One story claims he is the son of Brahman, while another says he created himself from water and seed.\nVishnu represents water, which symbolizes his role as the sustainer of life. He is the protector side of Brahman, known for upholding goodness and creation, and is identified with his incarnations — Krishna and Rama.\nShiva represents fire and is identified as the destructive power of the trimurti. However, he is also viewed as a positive force that cleanses and destroys evil, paving the way for new creation and a fresh start.\nVedas: In the Vedas we do not find any reference to the concept of Trinity. During the Rigvedic period, Vishnu was a minor solar deity, while Shiva was almost unknown. The Rigvedic hymns speak of Rudra, a fierce god of the skies and thunder, father of Maruts, who was invoked mostly as the healer with wondrous medicines. But we are not sure whether he was in any way connected with the Shiva of later times. The triple deities (Trimurthis) do exist in space and time, although it is difficult to explain the nature of their existence, as well as their true potentialities since they belong to the very highest realms of creation. In the human beings they exist beyond the mind as potentialities of the divinities of the super-mind or the divine mind, who are envisioned only by a handful of adept yogis in deep meditation. Seemingly there is nothing physical about them although in their ignorance people tend to consider them human beings with flesh and blood. From the experiences of adept yogis and self-realized souls, we understand that although the triple deities remain in their ethereal aspect as pure energies and consciousness with dimensions beyond our imagination and comprehension, they can assume physical form when they deem fit, appear anywhere in the universe at will, and manifest themselves in whatever way they choose. They are God’s most pleasing and benevolent aspects in the manifested creation, personifying His dynamic functions. They represent His will in cognizable forms with which the human mind can interact and relate well.\n\nThe cycle of nature: In reality they are the cycle of life. In creating anything, one needs to destroy something and to protect the  creation likewise. It might happen that one has to destroy  to create something new. If one destroys, in reality  eventually something new will be created. The cycle is always inter bonded with each other and human life needs to abide by this fact. So we are brought to the concept of the rotating cycle of nature. Everything will cease to exist one day but the trinity will remain. The god existing in the trinity or three persons (immeasurable planes) appear at the same time in three various roles. The difference lies in the appearances which become part of the majestic or magnificent illusion that the god entwines all around humankind.\n\n Brahma: In the Vedas, Brahma is the physical aspect (Viraj) of Isvara and enjoys a unique place as the highest in the pantheon. The Vedic hymns do not give the same importance to Vishnu and Shiva, who became prominent in the later Vedic period. In the Vedas, Brahma is the father of gods, humans and demons. In importance, he is next only to Brahman or his higher aspects namely Isvara and Hiranyagarbha. He is also the teacher and ruler of all beings. Hence, he is known as Brahma Prajapati. According to the Vedas after manifesting from Isvara, he created the worlds and beings with his mind powers. The Puranas present a slightly different version.
